Tram Nouinma<//username>
<Date>1575565757870</Date><rate>4</rate>< text>
After the gym and a bike ride at Shoreline I took Gavin here to refuel.  We were both hungry and was ready to feast.  I don't eat papusas often but for some reason I felt that it was my destiny to consume some.  This restaurant is very small and it gets busy and after eating here I can see why.

Service was spotty.  I couldn't tell if they were short because they were busy or if it's because they didn't care or was annoyed that it was busy.  That was the impression I felt.. because this place was busy I sent Gavin off to fend for himself so he can hunt down a table for us whilst I order and pay.  We tag team all the time when we need to.  He found a table whilst I ordered the chicken burrito bowl, a chicken burrito (w/o the pico), and their beef papusa.

Gavin's burrito and my burrito bowl (really a plate) was served w/in 15 minutes which isn't bad but the papusas took awhile.  They do make everything fresh but still.. 25-30 minutes for papusas isn't what I was expecting.  I had to go up and ask.

The papusas were delicious.. I will learn how to make it myself.<//text>

<user_id>101147706118471884534<//user_id>< username>

< Date>
1386377509214</Date>
<rating>4</rating>< review>
I usually come here for a late night dinner after a long day at work. They are usually open until 10 on weekdays.

They have a wide selection of food. I would suggest getting the papusas. They make it right in front of you after you order. I have had the enchiladas and burritos too. The meat is usually very juicy and flavorful. They have a liquor license and offer various beers.

The location isn't great (The shopping center it is located in can seem dark and deserted at night), but the restaurant itself is clean. The menu is large and easy to read and the staff wear custom shirts with the name of the restaurant. I think the owners are doing a good job of keeping the quality of the dining experience up.</review>

<Name>Exit Kiwi</Name><Date>1369028061953< /Date><Rating>4<//Rating><Text>I love pupusas, so I get excited every time I find a place that serves them. They're excellent here. Greasy (unfortunately this is expected) but flavorful and filling. They don't skimp on the cheese/meat etc., and have different options for fillings. < Text>
We randomly bumped into Ni-Mo for lunch. It was between the two places next door so this seemed like the best option.

There are 3-4 small tables on the sidewalk with 4 tables under the large awning. They are a good distance away from each other. They did not have one-use menus though.

I got the 5 handrolls combo which came with soup and salad. The rolls were pretty large, but they didn't taste good at all. Super pass.

The servers don't seem to be paying too much attention to the "line". An older couple came and asked for a table and was told to wait by the sushi chef who happened to peak outside. Then a younger couple came by 5-10 minutes later but was misunderstood to be first in line by one of the servers. The older couple waited an extra 20 minutes for their table.</Text>

<Pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOk2aEH7hPzYHBu1FhYiyBMFa3YJzLvZJWXy1f9=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipN_06F3l0AJcICGwwyRqtz-_IfZnd02joCgTliF=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</Pictures><gmap_id>0x808f9e704bf47b1d:0x1bd023b7bbd6f54c</gmap_id><user>107891048455871618661<//user><response>None<//response>< name>
Juana Tango< /name>
< text>
The pricing is extremely reasonable given Bay Area rents (12 buck lunches).  The portions in the lunch bento box were generous. The service was very efficient and friendly enough.  The hot tea was great - not too weak or strong.  There are vegetarian and omnivore options.  Seating is accessible,  armless. Place is clean,  food is fresh. Ambience is fine, but not amazing.  I think the flavors are not quite there to merit 5 stars,  but it is quite good.   Parking is usually on the same block.  To be honest I'm a little surprised given the good value and consistency that they aren't more crowded.  It may be folks prefer a peppier more hands on cheerleader type of server, or the slightly diner feel isn't fancy enough ambience for some. I like the things they do to be efficient like leaving the pot of tea,  the pitcher of water so you can refill yourself.  I know some folks prefer the more hands on hovering type of service that feels a bit more pampered,  but tbh I have always found that level of service a bit elitist. I appreciate not having a hawk like watchfulness to see when my last sip is gone and rush in to fill.  I find it more relaxing to do that for myself.
Somehow they've found the right balance of ensuring every need gets met (noticing when they forgot an item, quick to respond when we indicated wanting assistance -check) with allowing the space to not be overbearing. Only been here a couple of times,  but I'm sure we will continue to enjoy this venue when in the area.</text>

< Text>
Solid lunch spot. Had their lunch combo with chicken katsu and pork katsu. It came with a salad, bowl of rice, and miso soup for $10.95. Chicken katsu was made of thigh meat not breast which made it a little too fatty and oily for me. Overall good affordable lunch option in San Mateo. Don‚Äôt get their kalbi (beef short ribs) since the marinade is too bitter and the meat is too thin and get easily overcooked. We didn‚Äôt have to wait for a table either which was good. Service could be faster though.<//Text>

<date>1529332388339</date>< Review>
For basic sushi and sashimi, you can't beat this place. Fish is expertly cut and portions are generous. The rice in the sushi is nicely flavored.
Excellent agadashi tofu, too!
I have had sushi in may San Mateo restaurants in the past month, and none beat Ni Mo. For the freshest fish, the best portions and best sushi rice, Ni Mo beats them all, hands down.
If you are looking for clever fusion food, go elsewhere. For Japanese food, this is IT.</Review>

<Time>1582656523753</Time><user_id>108086852141163458238< /user_id>< Review>
Great location and I had resisted any poor reviews prior to moving in assuming. Despite the lack of visitors parking available as most use the spots as second permanent resident parking spots, unfortunately during my stay I've become very disappointed with management, several  instances concerning safety have occurred. Several instances of my door knob simply falling off out of nowhere occurred leaving a hole in my door, which management did not see this as a safety issue each time this was brought to their attention. This morning I was told that having a hole in my door was not a safety concern and the handy man would be by sometime tomorrow between 8am - 5pm to fix it. Why was this not fixed properly after the first occurrence and how am I to leave my home like this while I am at work?  Furthermore, instances of strangers moving my shed right up to the balcony was also not addressed in any way my management nor was there any concern. Strangers leaving random notes leaving phone numbers on my car were also again of no of concern with management. While the inside of my rented mobile home is nice, I'm disappointed in the way management has deal with such issues. Every rental community has pros and cons, I would expect safety issues to be prioritized. I will be moving out prior to my lease being expired for these reasons. I hope future residents will receive better service for this luxury rent being charged by this management company. I'll keep you guys updated on how much of my deposit I get back after hiring my own carpet cleaning professional and professional to clean the place the entire prior to my move out inspection...<//Review>

We were already folding our clothes once the owner came around. My dad followed up with the problem and the owner insisted that the machine works (since others were using it, unbeknownst to them that it probably wasn't rinsing their clothes--again it's a busy day so for some they just wanna wash and go).

< Review>
I really loved this place. Went with my family - my folks used to come here in the 70s and they said it looks exactly the same. I can't say the service was great but the food definitely was. 3 of us got the "32 pointer" and it was fantastic. It's got fried shrimp, smelt, catfish, clams, and frog legs with fries. All of it was great washed down with a couple of beers and a well-made old fashioned. I'll be back.< /Review>

5< /rating>
< text>
Even after having a full lunch, we drove by this location and said LETS EAT LUNCH AGAIN! Hahah. We could resist giving Newport Seafood a try during our trip here, no matter how full we were. We came here right after a lunch crowd and i'm glad we didnt have to fight with anyone for some lobsters. We ordered ours with garlic noodles and it was the best decision ever. The smallest lobster they had was a 4 pounder- we didn't even make a dent. We ended up taking it to-go and brought it on our flight home LOL. The meat on the lobster is thick and you don't feel skimped for the price you pay- definitely a must try if you visit SoCal.< /text>

<userid>101303881144060623742< /userid><Name>Active Ascension<//Name><Time>1568747108391< /Time><rate>1< /rate><Review>I walked into the dealership, happy from my experience at the Hyundai dealer in Dublin back in 2012, ready to buy a car and rate this place at five stars.

1.) First, when I arrive I say I am ready to buy, and this process needs to take under an hour, so lets fill out the paperwork now, get the details settled, and then I'll test drive the car to make sure there's nothing wrong with it. Well, they insist I drive the car first, and then after, sure enough, they take over an hour and a half to "work out a deal" with the bank. I'm aware that dealers use a "wearing you down" tactic by making you wait a long times so you just take a bad deal out of impatience-I gave them the benefit of the doubt and assumed this wasn't the case.
(Minus One Star)
-Note that they said it was a bank "requirement" that we get an extended warranty, since my credit isn't perfect and that would make the lender feel "safe" and give us a good deal. Sounded like total BULLSH**, but I figured, why not, I could probably use the warranty anyways.

2.) When they finally get us into a room to sign, they don't actually have papers.
No, they have a "DocuSign" tablet thing that, which not only seems FAR less secure than just doing things on paper, but also takes extra time to "flip" pages. I've bought cars at dealers before, usually it's boom-boom-boom, sign all these places and your done in less than 15 minutes. Not the case here.
(Minus One Star)

3.) During the horrible signing process, we are now running on being at this dealership for over 2 hours.
Then the DocuSign tablet "crashes" on the last page, and wouldn't you know it, they have no paper back ups, so we are left waiting over an hour before they get it back up.
(Minus One Star)

4.) We finally get everything wrapped up, and then the salesperson who had been "wheelin' and dealin" with the bank for us, comes and gives us one. single. key. I thought it was suspicious but more over insulting that when spending over 25 grand on a car, you can't give me an extra key for 200 bucks
-Don't worry, Hyundai of Serramonte does have a customers relations department that reached out via email after the purchase, and when I mentioned all these grievances, they responded with.... well they didn't, they just ignored me completely.
(Minus One Star)

5.) Last and best of all-
I'm not pointing fingers or anything, but the car I bought from them ends up getting STOLEN ONLY 11 DAYS AFTER I BOUGHT IT FROM THEM. Right out front of my home. No broken glass, alarm, or any notion of a forced entry. Come to hear from one the employees there that they actually sold a similar model car (SS Camaro) there after I purchased mine, and that car was stolen within a single day.
(MINUS 10 STARS)
Take note of the other one star reviews on here and DO NOT TRUST THEM. There is something not right going on over there.

Update: When I returned to the dealership to cancel my warranty, they never sent the paperwork to the warranty company. I called the warranty company 11 days after submitting the paperwork and they said they received nothing and it was still active. Incompetent and rude doesn't even begin to describe this place.</Review>< Pictures>

If could give a zero star, I would do so.  When I purchased my Kona 2018 back in June 2018, the sales sold me an Express Five Dent and Ding repair plan.  When I needed to make a claim for a dent in March 2019,  I found out that the dent repair only covers dent without any paint loss.  Well, how often do you have a dent without scrapping off paint?  Almost never!  So I decided to cancel the remaining insurance coverage, because it is not useful .

I had to go to Hyundai  dealership in personal to sign a cancellation form.  The gentleman who processed the paperwork on 4/12/2019  was helpful.  He told me that if I do not receive the refund check in the mail in a few weeks, I should contact Lorie in their Business Office.   I thought it would be a very straight forward process, as the contract itself stated that at anytime the plan can be canceled.

What awaits me next has been a nightmare.  A month passed and I still did  not receive my $840.83 cancellation refund.  Thus I called Express Five. on 5/13/2019. The service representative advised me that the cancellation was processed and approved on 4/25/2019, and all necessary documentations have been forwarded to Hyundai for them to issue me my refund  since 5/22/2019.  If  there are issues, I need to contact the dealer's business office directly.

Since 5/13/2019, I have contacted Hyundai business office many times and given the following run around:  have to wait for Express Five to pay Hyundai dealer in order to issue me the refund; the business office manager is not in: waiting for the controller Patty, who is the only one who has the authorization to sign the check, who works at another location, who does not have a phone number I can contact her, etc.  The excuses go on and on.  In this age and time, I cannot believe a firm of this size is UNABLE to issue a legitimate refund of less than $1000 within 5 business day.

It is now 6/10/2019,  more than 3 weeks have passed, I still have not seen my refund check.  If this is how Hyundai  Serramonte manages its businesses, buyers better beware and  go to another dealership.   What happened to customer service?  Hyundai Serramonte was so concerned about your response to the satisfaction survey after your initial vehicle purchase, but falls way short of providing satisfying customer service afterward.

I hope to get my refund soon.  If not, I will complain to the Better Business Bureau, Federal Trade Commission, and seek help from Channel  7's Mike Finney.</review>

<rate>1<//rate>< Review>
So disappointed. Spoke to the used car manager about selling my car. During the call he repeated back my name and car brand and model. He also assured me he would honor the Kelly Blue Book price range.

By Saturday, my name, according to the dealership receptionist, went from Lori to Sherryn. The car went from a Kia to a Toyota. And the price being offered on my car went from $3000-6000 range to $1,000.

I understand that details get lost in the translation when people don't write things down. So I could forgive the mix up in my name and my car's model.

But it's bad and unethical service when the customer is accused of lying when the staff comes in $2000 less than what was quoted on the phone.

I used to love this dealership. But now that it's under new ownership, buyers and sellers beware. The truth may not show up during your transaction. Stay away!< /Review>

< Text>
When they show you the price posted on the car, ask for the invoice (if they refuse, which they probably won't, ask to see their manager so they can give you the invoice). Request a price $1,000 below the invoice. If they refuse, say you're going somewhere else. Once they agree to the price, have them write it down on paper.

Before you sign your contract with them, make sure it is the price you agreed to- they WILL try to low ball you.

If you have a bad credit score, tell then you won't pay interest above 5%.

Tip: These guys are VERY pushy and they will try to make you feel guilty for not buying their car; even if you insist you are just browsing.

They will tell you the offer is only available for a limited time and that if you come back tomorrow, the offer might be gone. They're just trying to fool you.

I highly recommend walking away once they start with the pressure.

Good luck!< /Text>

<text>In all fairness, I cannot speak to the car buying experience at Hyundai of Serramonte, and most people probably won't have the experience I did. But I believe my experience does speak to their customer service, or lack thereof.

I went for a test drive in a Sonata plug in hybrid last night. Before getting in the car, the salesman told me the gas engine kicks in whenever the car goes over 35 mph, which I'm pretty sure is not true. He then turned me over to another guy to take me on the test drive. When we got into the car, the low gas indicator was on and the battery gauge showed low charge. I asked him if we needed to put some gas in, and he said we would be fine.

So we drove for about 5 minutes, including about a mile on the freeway. When we got off the freeway, a bright Check Hybrid System warning came on. I again asked if we should find a gas station, and he said it shouldn't be a problem. As we started getting on the freeway to head back, the car wasn't accelerating properly and then it dropped out completely, about 3/4 mile from the dealership.

At this point, I found the whole situation rather amusing. I sat in the car on the freeway shoulder for about 15 minutes before finally asking the guy if someone was coming to pick us up. He said he couldn't get a hold of anyone at the dealership, but he called Hyundai (Blue Link, I think) and said a tow truck should be there in an hour. I told him I needed to get back sooner to pick up my daughter, so we both started calling the dealership again. I kept getting voicemail, so I decided to walk.

When I got back to the dealership, I asked the vultures (salesmen) standing in front if I could speak to a manager. They pointed at one guy who was a Sales Manager. I asked to speak to a store manager, since I figured they would want to know what happened. He went into the back to find one and never came back out. Another Sales Manager asked if he could help and I told him what happened. He apologized and asked if there was anything he could do. I told him to put gas in their cars for a start. But most importantly, I told him to make sure they can be reached, if not by customers, at least by their employees, in case of emergency. Needless to say, I won't be calling them again.<//text>< pics>

< Text>
In all fairness, I cannot speak to the car buying experience at Hyundai of Serramonte, and most people probably won't have the experience I did. But I believe my experience does speak to their customer service, or lack thereof.

I went for a test drive in a Sonata plug in hybrid last night. Before getting in the car, the salesman told me the gas engine kicks in whenever the car goes over 35 mph, which I'm pretty sure is not true. He then turned me over to another guy to take me on the test drive. When we got into the car, the low gas indicator was on and the battery gauge showed low charge. I asked him if we needed to put some gas in, and he said we would be fine.

So we drove for about 5 minutes, including about a mile on the freeway. When we got off the freeway, a bright Check Hybrid System warning came on. I again asked if we should find a gas station, and he said it shouldn't be a problem. As we started getting on the freeway to head back, the car wasn't accelerating properly and then it dropped out completely, about 3/4 mile from the dealership.

At this point, I found the whole situation rather amusing. I sat in the car on the freeway shoulder for about 15 minutes before finally asking the guy if someone was coming to pick us up. He said he couldn't get a hold of anyone at the dealership, but he called Hyundai (Blue Link, I think) and said a tow truck should be there in an hour. I told him I needed to get back sooner to pick up my daughter, so we both started calling the dealership again. I kept getting voicemail, so I decided to walk.

When I got back to the dealership, I asked the vultures (salesmen) standing in front if I could speak to a manager. They pointed at one guy who was a Sales Manager. I asked to speak to a store manager, since I figured they would want to know what happened. He went into the back to find one and never came back out. Another Sales Manager asked if he could help and I told him what happened. He apologized and asked if there was anything he could do. I told him to put gas in their cars for a start. But most importantly, I told him to make sure they can be reached, if not by customers, at least by their employees, in case of emergency. Needless to say, I won't be calling them again.< /Text>

< text>
We had a great experience leasing a new car here last week with help from a lovely salesperson by the name of Bernz. My partner and I walked in to look at some Kia Souls that we heard this dealership had on the lot, and we quickly became interested in the new 2018 Hyundai Elantra GT once we set our eyes on it. We were extremely satisfied with the customer service and are happy to recommend this business (and Bernz) to our friends. I'd give it 5 stars, but we spent over 5 hours there and the majority of the time was waiting because they only had one finance person on site who was tied up with other customers ahead of us.
